          "body": "Genesis 18 opens with one of Scripture's most remarkable sentences: 'Now the LORD appeared to him' (18:1) — and then Abraham sees three men. The narrator has told the reader what Abraham does not yet fully know: divinity has arrived in human form. Abraham's response is saturated with Near Eastern hospitality conventions — he runs, bows to the earth, urges the guests to stay, offers water and bread, then produces a feast of fine flour cakes, curds, milk, and a choice calf (18:2-8). The extravagance of the meal is the text's signal: Abraham understands something significant is happening. He does not eat with the visitors; he stands and serves while they eat (18:8) — the posture of a host-servant, not a peer. The Epistle to the Hebrews draws the lesson explicitly: 'Do not neglect to show hospitality to strangers, for by this some have entertained angels without knowing it' (Hebrews 13:2). But the lesson of Genesis 18 runs deeper than hospitality: the God who is the LORD of all creation condescends to eat dust-and-ashes food under a tree in Canaan. The incarnation is not without precedent in the Old Testament; it is the fulfillment of a pattern of divine condescension that runs from Eden to Mamre to Bethlehem."
