          "title": "The birth promise renewed and Sarah's laughter rebuked",
          "body": "The question 'Where is Sarah your wife?' (18:9) is not asked from ignorance — it is asked to include her in what follows. The LORD's announcement, 'Sarah your wife will have a son' (18:10), is the third major iteration of the promise after 15:4 and 17:19. The biological context is stated bluntly by the narrator: Abraham and Sarah are old, advanced in age, and Sarah has passed the age of childbearing (18:11). Her laughter (18:12) is not joyful anticipation — the Hebrew *tsachaq* here carries the tone of incredulous mockery, the inward scorn of someone who has waited too long for a promise too long unfulfilled. She does not laugh at God's grace; she laughs at the anatomical specifics. The LORD's response is the chapter's theological center: 'Is anything too difficult for the LORD?' (*heyipale' min-yehovah dabar?*, 18:14). The word *pala* denotes what surpasses normal human capacity — the extraordinary, the miraculous. The canonical echo is precise: Jeremiah 32:17 ('Nothing is too difficult for You') and Jeremiah 32:27 ('Is anything too difficult for Me?') both cite this moment. When Sarah denies her laughter out of fear, the LORD does not relent: 'No, but you did laugh' (18:15). The correction is gentle but unflinching. The God who makes impossible promises also holds His witnesses to truthfulness about their response to them."
