          "body": "Verses 22-32 constitute the longest recorded intercessory prayer dialogue in the Torah and one of the most theologically revealing passages about prayer in all of Scripture. Abraham 'drew near' (*nagash*, 18:23) — the same verb used of the priest approaching the altar. He begins with a question that is simultaneously a protest and a petition: 'Will You indeed sweep away the righteous with the wicked?' (18:23). The ground of the appeal is the LORD's own character: 'Far be it from You to do such a thing... Shall not the Judge of all the earth deal justly?' (18:25). Abraham does not flatter God or appeal to divine mercy in the abstract; he appeals to divine character as a constraint on divine action. Six rounds of intercession follow, each lowering the threshold: fifty, forty-five, forty, thirty, twenty, ten (18:24-32). With each iteration Abraham frames his approach with a mixture of deference ('I have ventured to speak,' 'I am but dust and ashes,' 'may the Lord not be angry') and boldness (each new number lower than the last). The LORD grants every request. The intercession stops at ten not because Abraham runs out of boldness but because ten was the minimum socially recognizable community in ancient Israel — a minyan, a household quorum. Sodom will not even have ten. What the chapter does not say is as important as what it says: Abraham does not pray for Lot by name. He prays for the righteous generally. The chapter implies that the absence of even ten righteous makes Sodom irredeemable — a fact Genesis 19 will confirm."
