          "body": "Genesis 18 stands at the head of a canonical trajectory of priestly intercession: Moses standing in the breach (Exodus 32:11-14; Psalm 106:23), Elijah at Carmel, Jeremiah's anguished prayers for Judah (Jeremiah 14:7-9), Paul's desire to be accursed for Israel's sake (Romans 9:3). In each case, the intercessor stands between the righteous God and the people He is about to judge, not to deny God's justice but to invoke His mercy. The NT identifies Jesus Christ as the ultimate intercessor — 'He always lives to make intercession' (Hebrews 7:25) — who does not merely appeal to God's character but embodies and satisfies it. What Abraham could only ask ('Far be it from You to slay the righteous with the wicked'), Christ accomplished: at the cross, the righteous One absorbed the judgment of the wicked so that the Judge of all the earth could be both just and the justifier of those who believe (Romans 3:26). Genesis 18's question — 'Shall not the Judge of all the earth deal justly?' — finds its full answer not at Sodom but at Calvary."
